🔴 IMPORTANT TRUTH (read this first)

👉 When input is a NUMBER (not array)
👉 You are NOT searching an index
👉 You are searching a VALUE

So the pointer rules are slightly different.

Step 1: Always ask this ONE question

❓ Am I finding an EXACT value or a BOUND (first true)?

Case A — Exact match

Example:
Find integer x such that x*x == n

Case B — First true (Lower Bound)

Example:
Find smallest x such that x*x >= n
(square root / nth root problems)

Step 2: Pointer rules (THIS is what you want)
🔹 CASE A: EXACT MATCH (number problems)

👉 You want only equality

while i <= j


if condition(mid) < target → i = mid + 1

if condition(mid) > target → j = mid - 1

if equal → return mid

✅ Use this when:

perfect square check

exact power check

search a number

🔹 CASE B: LOWER BOUND (MOST number problems like sqrt)

👉 Pattern:

false false false true true true


👉 Goal: first true

while i <= j


Rules:

if condition(mid) is TRUE →
👉 keep mid, go left
👉 j = mid - 1

if condition(mid) is FALSE →
👉 go right
👉 i = mid + 1

✅ Final answer is i

🔥 GOLDEN RULE (write this on paper)

If you write j = mid → use while i < j
If you write j = mid - 1 → use while i <= j

In number problems, we almost always use:

j = mid - 1


So:

while i <= j

Why NOT j = mid in number problems?

Because:

mid is a VALUE, not an index

keeping mid can cause infinite loop

mid - 1 guarantees movement

Simple decision table 🧠
Situation	Use
Searching in ARRAY	j = mid possible
Searching in NUMBERS	❌ avoid j = mid
sqrt / nth root	j = mid - 1
first true	lower bound
exact value	normal binary search
Final mental shortcut (VERY IMPORTANT)

Say this in your head 👇

“This is a NUMBER problem, not array
→ I must move pointers strictly
→ so I use mid + 1 or mid - 1 only”

